# web-nav-qwen2.5-coder-14b — light, fast model for browser-agent planning + navigation.
#
# Why not qwen3-grounded: it is 17 GB and does NOT fit a 12 GB GPU, so it
# partially offloads to CPU and crawls through the many-step navigator loop (~18 tok/s in a
# local benchmark). qwen2.5-coder:14b is 9 GB, fits fully on the GPU (~29 tok/s), and coder
# models are reliable at the nested JSON action schemas browser agents emit — in the same
# benchmark it produced a correct click action while qwen3-grounded returned an EMPTY action
# list (valid-but-useless, the real failure mode since Ollama grammar-forces JSON validity).
#
# num_ctx 16384: the Navigator receives the page's filtered interactive-element tree every
# step. The global OLLAMA_CONTEXT_LENGTH is only 8k, which truncates that tree and makes the
# agent "lose" elements. 16k fits in the remaining VRAM (9 GB weights + KV cache < 12 GB) and
# stops that truncation.
#
# NOTE: a browser agent can OVERRIDE this with a per-request num_ctx — the original
# browser-agent client hardcoded num_ctx=64000 (helper.ts:345), and under that this 14B
# ran at 64K (9 GB weights + 64K KV can spill to CPU on 12 GB). This num_ctx applies when
# the client sends none; for long pages prefer web-nav-qwen3.5-9b (fits 64K at ~6.9 GB).
# In WebBrain, set "Context window (tokens)" equal to this num_ctx.
#
# temperature 0.2: near-deterministic, repeatable actions without hard-0 looping.
#
# Use ONE model for every agent role so Ollama keeps it resident — pointing roles at
# different models forces a ~13 s model reload on every swap.
FROM qwen2.5-coder:14b
PARAMETER num_ctx 16384
PARAMETER temperature 0.2
